message.content:
We need to “build up” the liabilities from the transactions that represent unpaid supplier‐purchases that the company must eventually pay (i.e. those that use an “Account Payable” payment method and are marked “Unpaid”). (The “Initial” balance in these transactions is zero because none of the “Initial20231231001” entries represent a liability.) 

Step 1. Look only at the “Purchase” transactions. (Other entries such as expenses, sales or cash/bank/asset items are not “liability” items.)  

Step 2. From the “Purchase” transactions identify those that are “Unpaid” and where the payment method indicates that the amount will eventually be “Account Payable.” The following “Purchase” rows meet that criterion and contribute the following amounts (all amounts are taken directly from the “amount” field in the record):

• Purchase20231231001: 180,000.00  
• Purchase20231231003: 150,000.00  
• Purchase20231231004: 350,000.00  
• Purchase20231231013: 140,000.00  
• Purchase20231231014: 400,000.00  
• Purchase20231231016: 30,000.00  
• Purchase20231231018: 60,000.00  
• Purchase20231231019: 60,000.00  
• Purchase20231231020: 350,000.00  
• Purchase20231231021: 100,000.00  

Step 3. Sum these unpaid “Purchase” amounts:
  180,000.00  
+ 150,000.00 = 330,000.00  
+ 350,000.00 = 680,000.00  
+ 140,000.00 = 820,000.00  
+ 400,000.00 = 1,220,000.00  
+ 30,000.00  = 1,250,000.00  
+ 60,000.00  = 1,310,000.00  
+ 60,000.00  = 1,370,000.00  
+ 350,000.00 = 1,720,000.00  
+ 100,000.00 = 1,820,000.00

Step 4. Because none of the “Initial” entries started out as a liability, the “Total Liabilities Initial Value” is 0.00. Then the “Total Liabilities End Value” (after all the transactions have been recorded) is the sum of these outstanding purchase costs: 1,820,000.00

Thus, in our final balance‐sheet the liabilities item is computed as:
  Initial Liabilities: 0.00  
  Ending Liabilities: 1,820,000.00
